			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">chopper, I'm using a GeForce FX 5200 (128Mb) card and it runs just fine.  I have a gig of ram, though.
<br />

<br />
Stunzed, I just thought of something else!  Do you know how your swap file is set up?  Whatever you do, do NOT allow Windows to manage your page file!!  Windows is smart...but it ain't THAT smart, hahaha.
<br />

<br />
What you do is make sure that your page file is set to a static size: preferably 25% more than the amount of ram you have in the system.  There are pros and cons to this:
<br />

<br />
Cons:
<br />
- Even if your system doesn't need to page much data at the time, the file will STILL be "x" megabytes in size.  In other words, that static size is always reserved.
<br />

<br />
Pros:
<br />
- Interestingly enough, the con I listed above is ALSO the pro.  The process of "File I/O" is the single largest resource-intensive action a computer can currently perform (as a function of elapsed time).  Because you're typically dealing with hardware that runs a HELL of a lot slower than your system BUS.  So, you are bottlenecked at the disk-drive level.  Now, if you allow Windows to manage your page file size, then Windows will damned-near constantly be doing file I/O operations while you're playing a game...causing everything else to slow down in the process.
<br />

<br />
So, if you have not messed with the page file since you last reinstalled Windows, then it is by default set to have Windows manage the size.  You need to change this ASAP.  This is not necessarily the cause of the specific problem you are dealing with, but it is definitely the cause of others.
<br />

<br />
A "windows-managed" page file has application elsewhere, definitely.  Just not in gaming.  We tend to need every last piece of horsepower we can squeeze out of our systems <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
To do this:
<br />
Start --&gt; control panel --&gt; system.  Click on the "Advanced" tab.  Now, under "Performance", click on the button labeled "Settings".  In the new window that pops up, click on the "Advanced" tab.  Down at the bottom of that window, you'll see a section labeled "Virtual Memory".  Click on the button labeled "Change".  In the new window that opens up, make sure that "Custom Size" is the radio-button that is checked.  Then, enter in the same number for "Initial size" as you do for "maximum size".  This number should be, approximately, YOUR_CURRENT_RAM + 25% (just a general rule of thumb, and is the number I was taught by local sysadmins at a research facility I used to work at).
<br />

<br />
Optional:
<br />
- If you have more than one drive, and each drive is on a different bus, place the page file on the drive that is on a *different* bus than the drive EQ2 is installed on.  This will allow "paging" to take place simultaneously with EQ2-required reads/writes.
<br />

<br />
- When you defrag, realize first that you cannot defrag the paging file.  And this can be problematic when you have a large page file.  So, before you defrag, go *back* to the place above where you set the file size, and check the radio button for "no page file".  This will free up the space currently used by your page file, allowing you to defrag those sectors.<br />_________________<br />EQ1:  Mujahid Mukhtaar - Arch Lich, Solusek Ro (Retired)
<br />
EQ2:  Mujahid Mukhtaar - Summoner, Mistmoore
<br />

<br />
